\end{align*}

We see that as $t \to \infty$, the transient terms involving $C_1$ and $C_2$ decay exponentially due to the damping term $- \frac{\gamma}{2m}$. Thus, after enough time has passed, only the steady-state solution remains:

\begin{align*}
x_{ss}(t) &= \frac{A/m}{\left( \omega_0^2 - \omega^2 \right)^2 + \left( \frac{\gamma \omega}{m} \right)^2} \left[ \left( \omega_0^2 - \omega^2 \right) \cos(\omega t) + \frac{\gamma \omega}{m} \sin(\omega t) \right], \\
\dot{x}_{ss}(t) &= \frac{-A/m}{\left( \omega_0^2 - \omega^2 \right)^2 + \left( \frac{\gamma \omega}{m} \right)^2} \left[ \left( \omega_0^2 - \omega^2 \right) \omega \sin(\omega t) - \frac{\gamma \omega^2}{m} \cos(\omega t) \right].
\end{align*}

Plugging these expressions into our earlier integral formula for $P_{avg}$, we get:

\begin{align*}
P_{avg} &= \frac{\gamma}{T} \int_0^T \left\{ \frac{A^2/m^2}{\left[ \left( \omega_0^2 - \omega^2 \right)^2 + \left( \frac{\gamma \omega}{m} \right)^2 \right]} \left[ \left( \omega_0^2 - \omega^2 \right) \omega \sin(\omega t) - \frac{\gamma \omega^2}{m} \cos(\omega t) \right]^2 \right\} dt \\
